postcontent: DWM Luger P-08 Imperial Navy, Cal. 9mm, Ser. 9XX n. Dated 1916. Rare and minty. The 1916, as you know, is the scarcest of all WWI Navy Lugers. The condition is outstanding, about 97-98+% of the original blue.  The loss is just sharp edge slivering, a couple small areas of the muzzle that have surface pin pricks and the usual side plate wear.. Probably caused by the holster. The gripstraps have not even started to gray. The condition of this is gun is unusually fine considering most of them went to sea and were subject to salt water corrosion.  All numbers match. After the war certain minty guns were selected for export. This gun is stamped very lightly on the right slide rail, Germany. The left side of the barrel group has the Imperial WWI marks, and is stamped Crown, Crown/M, Crown/M. The barrel is also stamped twice with a Crown. The front sight is dated 1916 like the receiver. The wooden grips are just super, showing almost no wear. Not a crack, chip or any flattened points. The slide rails, bolt face and feed ramp show very little use. The bore, like the rest of the gun, is mirror bright with razor sharp rifling. The gun comes with one correct three ring wooden based magazine.

title: Want To Buy:  ITHACA MODEL 72 LEVER ACTION RIFLE
postcontent:
HI, NEED SOME HELP !!  pics. of old lifter.. Having trouble with a ITHACA MODEL 72 lever action .22LR. Carrier is bad. Have not been able to find one. I have tried several parts supply houses and several of the old ITHACA repair shops. I either need a machining print or another GOOD carrier to copy. I have a machinist / gunsmith willing to make one. He tried coping the old one, it was to bad of shape to copy!! I NEED a parts rifle with working carrier / receiver... or a working rifle !!! Found a couple rifles but they were having the same problem as I am having with my rifle!!! HERE IS WHAT I HAVE FOUND OUT: Ithaca Model 72 is a variant of the Erma Werke of Dachau, Germany Model EG-71.. Made from 1973 to 1979, this rifle was offered in .22 Long Rifle and .22 Magnum only. It had an 18 1/2" barrel. The lever gun was designed by Erma of Germany. Some years after Ithaca stopped production Iver Johnson picked it up and marketed it as the "Wagonmaster". My gunsmith had a Iver Johnson " Wagonmaster "in the shop when he was working on my rifle. He told me it used a lifter- not a carrier to cycle the round. Was told It is basically the same rifle that Henry is producing today. Ordered a carrier from Henry ( H001) they are not the same!!
I saw where Numrich had a 22mag carrier. Can it be modified to work with 22lr?Not according to my gunsmith and Numrich..Look at the picture for the .22 mag. carrier and the picture of mine.They are differant.He called and talked to them about 6 months ago.
Places I have tried so far:
Western Gun Parts Ltd. (W.G.P. Ltd.)- Canada -- we do not have any Carriers !!
Sharp's Guns ,Canada -- we do not have any Carriers !!

EBAY -- we do not have any Carriers !!
OUT BACK GUN PARTS, INC. -- we do not have any Carriers !!
Hoosier Gun Works -- No parts for rifle and you've tried all the source we would have!!
FlyingWoof - aol.com -- we do not have any Carriers !!
Jeremiah Logsdon -- Ithaca Gun Company— We do not carry parts for or service the 72.
 
 I should have known when I got the rifle in a trade something was up.Thought I was getting a deal...We have been working on this for 6-7 months now with no luck..My gunsmith tried to copy the old one just to much was missing to get it to work!!
